January is National Mentoring Month! There are so many amazing opportunities in GI to become a mentor. Dr. Amanda Levos at GIPS shares why she decided to become a mentor: "The impact of a mentor is life-changing! I have had the opportunity to personally connect with several amazing young adults through TeamMates Mentoring Program, witness the result of STRIVE mentoring with our refugee families, and advocate for the statewide needs through serving as a Mentor Nebraska board member. Each relationship has been an opportunity and space to amplify young adult voices and provide them the encouragement, support, and resources they need to reach their personal goals. Now more than ever, you can be that consistent adult presence by taking one hour a week to be there and show our students that they matter." #NationalMentoringMonth #BeThere

Ellen Ochoa is an American engineer, former astronaut, and former director of the Johnson Space Center. While lack of legal immigration status is a vulnerability commonly exploited by traffickers, U.S. citizens can experience human trafficking as well. Human trafficking occurs any time an individual is forced, defrauded, or coerced into participating in a commercial sex act or performing labor. If you or someone you know is experiencing trafficking/exploitation, you can call the National Human Trafficking Hotline (1-888-373-7888) or contact your local crisis center: https://www.nebraskacoalition.org/get_help/:=:https://www.nebraskacoalition.org/get_help/help.html

While anyone can be a victim of human trafficking, it's important that we recognize the connection of trafficking to race, gender, and migration! Learn more about the signs of human trafficking: https://humantraffickinghotline.org/human-trafficking/recognizing-signs?gclid=Cj0KCQjw_4-SBhCgARIsAAlegrWbD47vQEeBT1puR0UJ_6ktJmFwfKaDLqJfmS38hh8q8xw8uBotMNoaArETEALw_wcB:=:https://humantraffickinghotline.org/human-trafficking/recognizing-signs

In her ninth decade, Dolores Huerta is still crushing it. The labor leader and civil rights activist is proof that if you‚Äôre intent on making the world an even playing field, then nothing can slow you down. Huerta has won the Eleanor Roosevelt Award for Human Rights and the Presidential Medal of Freedom, as well as being the first Latina inducted into the National Women‚Äôs Hall of Fame. ‚ÄúI never felt overlooked because I didn‚Äôt expect any kind of recognition. I think that‚Äôs very typical of women.‚Äù

Toni Morrison is one of the most celebrated authors in the world with her catalogue of books including, ‚ÄúThe Bluest Eye,‚Äù ‚ÄúSong of Solomon,‚Äù and ‚ÄúHome.‚Äù Her work often grappled with issues of race, class, and gender equity, always with a focus on African American culture. During her career, Toni Morrison won MANY prestigious awards including the Pulitzer Price, the presidential Medal of Freedom, and she was the first Black woman to be awarded the Nobel Prize in literature. No one could write on the experience of Black American life quite like her, and no one has since. Through her work at Random House publishing, she was also able to edit works and support other incredible Black writers such as Toni Cade Bambara, Gayl Jones, and Angela Davis. Toni Morrison not only dedicated her work to sharing #BlackStories, but her dedication to making space for other Black women and authors to write about our history through the lenses of magical realism and historical fiction was unprecedented. The far-reaching impacts of her work cannot be understated, and her legacy is truly #legendary.

bell hooks was an author, professor, feminist, and social activist whose work focused on examining and uplifting the works of other Black writers while helping provide academic theory to support political organizing happening on the ground. Her extensive catalogue of written works and academic lectures covered topics such as race, class, gender, art, history, sexuality, mass media, and feminism. Some of her most well-known books being ‚ÄúAin‚Äôt I a Woman: Black Women and Feminism‚Äù and ‚ÄúFeminism is for Everybody‚Äù are now considered standard texts in intersectional feminist circles. We would be remiss if we didn‚Äôt acknowledge the contributions and legacy of bell hooks. When speaking on feminism bell hooks once said, ‚ÄúSexism has never rendered women powerless. It has either suppressed their strength or exploited it.‚Äù It is because of the vision and tireless work of #Blackfeminists like bell hooks, that we are reminded that even in our oppression, the experiences and wisdom of Black women continues to lead the way to liberation for all women. #bellhooks was many things, but at her core, she was always an educator challenging us to learn, grow, and seek resolutions through our challenges. ‚ÄúFor me, forgiveness and compassion are always linked: how do we hold people accountable for wrongdoing and yet at the same time remain in touch with their humanity enough to believe in their capacity to be transformed?‚Äù We thank her for her contributions, providing us new perspectives which empower women and the tools to be more inclusive in our feminist movements. #LessonsLearned #BlackHerstoryMonth #EmpoweredWomenEmpowerWomen

As a self-described ‚ÄúBlack, lesbian, mother, warrior, poet,‚Äù #BlackFeminist Audre Lorde dedicated her life to grappling with the critical and often intersecting injustices of racism, classism, sexism, and homophobia. She was a vigilant champion for Black queer women whose critiques of the racism within feminist movements offered a voice to Black women who often felt unseen and left behind. An iconic Black writer and poet, Lorde‚Äôs work coined phrases like ‚Äúyour silence will not protect you,‚Äù which have become central chants in the contemporary protests aimed to #eliminateracism and #empowerwomen. Lorde, a longtime social justice warrior, helped forge the blueprint to build communities that nurture our spirits and provide lessons learned on how love and radical self-care is essential to movements dismantling systemic injustice. Her radical perspectives helped pave the way for the contemporary radical Black feminists of today and created pathways for unity across the social divides she navigated in her own life. ‚ÄúI write for those women who do not speak, for those who do not have a voice because they were so terrified, because we are taught to respect fear more than ourselves. We‚Äôve been taught that silence would save us, but it won‚Äôt.‚Äù - Audre Lorde ‚Ä® #BlackHerstoryMonth #EmpoweredWomenEmpowerWomen

Today, May 3, 2022, is Asian American/Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander Women's Equal Pay Day. The average Asian American/Native Hawaiian/Pacific Islander woman is paid $0.75 for every $1.00 paid white, non-Hispanic men, losing about $400k over a 40-year career. In order to make up for lost wages, they have to work longer hours, multiple jobs, and often, past retirement age. In 2021 AANHPI Equal Pay Day was March 9th, meaning, AANHPI women have to work an extra 55 days this year! For certain communities, the wage gap is far greater. Even within high earning fields, Asian women are paid less than their male counterparts. It‚Äôs time for Equal Pay for All!

The STAND AGAINST RACISM 21 Day Challenge starts tomorrow! Join YWCA USA for the Stand Against Racism Challenge, April 4th through May 2nd. The Stand Against Racism Challenge is designed to create dedicated time and space to build more effective social justice habits, particularly those dealing with issues of race, power, privilege, and leadership. You will be presented with challenges such as reading an article, listening to a podcast, reflecting on personal experience and more. Participation in an activity like this helps us to discover how racial injustice and social injustice impact our community, to connect with one another, and to identify ways to dismantle racism and other forms of discrimination. This is an exciting opportunity to dive deep into racial equity and social justice. YWCA Hartford Region wants to thank and acknowledge Dr. Eddie Moore Jr., Debby Irving, and Dr. Marguerite Penick for their leadership in the field of racial equity as exhibited in their 21 Day Racial Equity and Habit Building Challenge and the movement they helped to initiate. YWCA‚Äôs content is independently designed, written, and curated by YWCA staff as part of racial equity and social justice programs offered to the community. WE ENCOURAGE YOU TO TAKE THE CHALLENGE! When you register, under where did you hear about the Stand Against Racism Challenge, select other and enter YWCA Hartford Region. https://standagainstracism.org/about/stand-against-racism-challenge/

Satellite images of a Chinese shipyard show a vessel that is raising concerns that China is developing a new type of nuclear submarine. Analysts told Reuters that the images of Huludao Port in Liaoning show a vessel that looks like a submarine, but it is unclear if it is an upgrade for an existing one or the development of a new class of boats. The Pentagon issued a report in November saying the Chinese navy was likely to build a new submarine with vertical launch capabilities designed for cruise missiles. Storage areas that are covered up near the submarine could house quieter propulsion equipment or missile launch tubes, analysts added. Vertical launch tubes would allow improved tracking capabilities of missiles fired from China‚Äôs submarines, improving their ‚Äúhunter-killer‚Äù capacity.

Sadie Tanner Mossell Alexander has lived a life of many firsts. In 1921, she became the first black person in the nation to earn a Ph.D. in economics. But that's not all, 3 years later she earned a law degree and became the first black woman to pass the Pennsylvania bar exam and become a lawyer. In 1947, President Truman added her to his Committee on Civil Rights, and 30 years later President Carter appointed her Chair of the White House Conference on Aging that aimed to address social and economic needs of the eldery. . . . . . . . . #blackhistory #blackhistorymonth #TodayTomorrowAlways #historicalfigures #civilrights #happyblackhistorymonth #socialactivism #communityaction #historyincolor #youthpower #youthmatter #justice #lookingback #BlackHistoryMonth2022

What's the difference between a bequest and a beneficiary? A bequest is property given in a will. One of the most popular ways to create an endowment is to mention the Jewish community as a bequest in your will. The simplest way to begin this process is by speaking with your estate planning attorney about your legacy wishes. A beneficiary is someone who is legally designated to receive the benefits of a trust, will, or life insurance policy. Naming the Jacobson Jewish Community Foundation as a beneficiary of your life insurance policy and/or IRA is a tax effective way to create an endowment. Visit https://jjcf.planningyourlegacy.org/beneficiary-designations to learn more about how to do this! Information contained herein was accurate at the time of posting. The information on this website is not intended as legal or tax advice. For such advice, please consult an attorney or tax advisor.

JFS and B'nai Torah Congregation are proud to present Fentanyl Awareness and Harm Reduction, an important community event, open to teens and adults, on Tuesday, Jan. 25 via zoom at 7 pm. Fentanyl, a drug 50 to 100 times stronger than Heroin, is being mixed into cocaine, Xanax, MDMA, and other street and prescription drugs, causing a large spike in drug overdose deaths. Fentanyl was implicated in over 75% of unintentional deaths in 2020 and is the number one cause of death in 18-45 year-olds. We will be discussing the use of social media to sell and purchase drugs, how to talk to your teen about substance use and experimentation, and ways to detect and prevent fentanyl overdose.
